Blog

Target IP: 10.10.219.83

Billy Joel made a blog on his home computer and has started working on it. It's going to be so awesome!
Enumerate this box and find the 2 flags that are hiding on it! Billy has some weird things going on his laptop. Can you maneuver around and get what you need? Or will you fall down the rabbit hole...
In order to get the blog to work with AWS, you'll need to add blog.thm to your /etc/hosts file.

Reconnaissance


I added the blog.thm in my /etc/hosts file.


There are four TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH, HTTP, and SMB. I will start enumeration with the SMB application as it allows guest login.

Enumeration

Port 139 and 445: SMB


Using guest login to access the SMB application, I downloaded the three files located at BillySMB SMB share. I have write privileges over this SMB share. The three files are shown above. The file check-this.png QR code file looks interesting.


Using an online QR code decoder, I managed to decode this file. It links to a YouTube music.


The file Alice-White-Rabbit.jpg does not contain anything useful either. I extracted the hidden data rabbit_hole.txt which is not helpful. The content of this file is shown above.

Port 80: HTTP

The WordPress webpage above is displayed for this application. The target is running WordPress 5.0.


Using the command wpscan --url http://blog.thm --enumerate u, I enumerated for the usernames of this application. I successfully obtained two usernames: kwheel and bjoel.


I performed a password attack against this blog application on XMLrpc with the command wpscan --password-attack xmlrpc --url http://blog.thm -U kwheel,bjoel -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt -t 20. The two usernames I used are kwheel and bjoel. I successfully managed to obtain the password cutiepie1 for the user kwheel.


And I successfully logged into the blog application using the credential kwheel:cutiepie1. Now I have access to the web application. However, I did not find anything that I could exploit using this web application. Time to enumerate harder.


After doing a Google search for Wordpress 5.0, I obtained the verified exploit above. Since this exploit is in Metasploit, I will use this against the target machine.

Exploitation


I used the exploit multi/http/wp_crop_rce. The options I initialised for this exploit are shown above.


And running the exploit worked! Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as www-data.

Privilege Escalation


The wp-config.php contains the credential above. Now I have the credential for the database application for this web application.


A user called bjoel exists on this machine. The interesting files are shown above for this user. The user.txt located at this user's directory is invalid.


An interesting file called Billy_Joel_Termination_May20-2020.pdf exists. I transferred this file to my machine. The content of this pdf file is shown above. Apparently this user was sacked for misusing USB. Maybe I can find something useful in this machine? But I do not have access to this directory.


I gained access to the MySQL application using the credential wordpressuser:LittleYellowLamp90!@. There is a database called blog with a table wp_users, as shown above. I tried to crack the password of user bjoel, but I had no luck.


There is an interesting binary called /usr/sbin/checker with SUID bit set. Executing this binary does not do anything, other than print "Not an admin".


However, using ltrace against this binary shows an environmental variable called admin is used.


I used the command export admin=1 to create a new environmental variable and set it to true.


And bingo. Now I have a root shell access on the target machine.
